        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 6-year-old girl from the Czech Republic who is brought in by her parent because of repeated cold symptoms after starting regular contact with other children, which is a common setting for frequent coughs and colds in young children attending day care [MEDDIALOG:J06.9:0]. Over the last few days she has had nasal congestion, a runny nose, and cough, with the family describing it as another “cold” [MEDDIALOG:J06.9:0, MEDDIALOG:J06.9:5]. Today she also says her tummy hurts, a symptom that can occur with acute upper respiratory infection [SNOMED:J06.9].\n\nOn appearance, {patientName} looks tired and clingier than usual but remains alert, interactive, and able to drink fluids. Her nose is stuffy and she has an intermittent cough, and her parent reports low-grade fever with the current illness [MEDDIALOG:J06.9:5]. There is no evidence provided for severe respiratory distress, so she is portrayed as uncomfortable but not toxic-appearing.\n\nAt home, {patientName} lives with her family and attends kindergarten/day care, where she is exposed to other children during the winter season, a context associated in the evidence with frequent colds and coughs [MEDDIALOG:J06.9:0]. She enjoys drawing, toy animals, and simple playground games when well. Her parent has become worried because several respiratory illnesses have occurred over recent months, though this episode is being assessed as an uncomplicated upper respiratory infection rather than a serious lower respiratory illness [MEDDIALOG:J06.9:0, MEDDIALOG:J06.9:5]."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
